[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(3) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "One fourth part.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Both day and night were divided into four parts. All orders standing in their respective place, the reading occupied the morning and the worship the afternoon. It is the latter which is now made prominent, as the former had been prominent in the preceding chapter.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Nehemiah 9:3",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Nehemiah 9:3",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They stood up and read in the book of the law — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That is, the Levites stood up in a place built for them, and read the law as they did before, interpreting the sense of what they read. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "One fourth part of the day",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " — To wit, for three hours; for there were reckoned twelve hours in their day. Probably they began to read after the morning sacrifice, at which time divers religious people used to be present, and continued reading till the sixth hour, that is, till midday; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and another fourth part — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Namely, from midday to the time of the evening sacrifice; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "they confessed — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Both God’s mercies, as appears from the following prayer, and their own sins, as is expressed ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 9:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", this day being chiefly set apart for the work of confession and humiliation; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and worshipped the Lord their God — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Partly by their acknowledgment and adoration of his wonderful mercy, in forgiving their sins, and saving them from the judgments which they had deserved, and for giving them his law, and the knowledge thereof; and partly, by imploring his further grace and mercy to them. The work of a fast-day is good work; and we should endeavour to make a day’s work, a good day’s work, of it.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "9:1-3 The word will direct and quicken prayer, for by it the Spirit helps our infirmities in prayer. The careful study of God's word will more and more discover to us our own sinfulness, and the plenteousness of his salvation; thus it calls us to mourn for sin, and to rejoice in him. Every discovery of the truth of God, should render us more unwearied in attendance on his sacred word, and on his worship.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The festival lasted from the 15th day of the 7th month to the first. The 22nd day was a day of solemn observance ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 8:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". One day seems to have been allowed the people for rest; and then the work of repentance, for which they had shown themselves ready ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 8:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", was taken in hand, and a general fast was proclaimed. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "3. they … read in the book of the law—Their extraordinary zeal led them to continue this as before.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "one fourth part of the day—that is, for three hours, twelve hours being the acknowledged length of the Jewish day (Joh 11:9). This solemn diet of worship, which probably commenced at the morning sacrifice, was continued for six hours, that is, till the time of the evening sacrifice. The worship which they gave to the Lord their God, at this season of solemn national humiliation, consisted in acknowledging and adoring His great mercy in the forgiveness of their great and multiplied offenses, in delivering them from the merited judgments which they had already experienced or which they had reason to apprehend, in continuing amongst them the light and blessings of His word and worship, and in supplicating the extension of His grace and protection.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
